 Except remember that $750 million loan that Och-Ziff took out at the IPO? =
Och-Ziff/Sculptor has paid =E2=80=9Ctax-deferred distributions=E2=80=9D to =
its partners: Effectively Sculptor/Och-Ziff=E2=80=99s partners were able to=
 take out cash in excess of the company=E2=80=99s income without paying tax=
es on it, deferring the taxes. At this point, if they sold for $11.15 per s=
hare, they would have =E2=80=9Csignificant taxable gain in excess of procee=
ds to be received in the transaction,=E2=80=9D meaning that much of the $11=
.15 would go to taxes. To avoid that, Och wants a buyer to keep the partner=
ship around and let him keep his partnership units until he decides to conv=
ert them. This is potentially a pain for the buyer, who might not=C2=A0want=
 Och around as a partner, but it is, says Sculptor, the price of his suppor=
t.

There are basically three sets of interests here:
=09Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders want the deal that gives them the highes=
t price per share.=09Jimmy Levin wants the deal that lets him keep his job =
at the highest pay rate.=09Dan Och wants the deal that gives him the highes=
