At a big bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0or other big financial firm, or other big comp=
any generally =E2=80=94=C2=A0most contracts are fulfilled by computer. Ofte=
n the contracts are also negotiated by computer =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you open =
a credit card on a company=E2=80=99s website, probably no human negotiated =
its terms with you =E2=80=94=C2=A0but often they aren=E2=80=99t. Often the =
process is:
=09A human at the bank negotiates a contract (a mortgage, an exotic derivat=
ive, a corporate loan restructuring, whatever) with a human counterparty.=
=09The human at the bank types the terms of the contract into the bank=E2=
=80=99s computer systems, or hands the contract to some other, lower-paid h=
uman at the bank to type them in.=09The bank=E2=80=99s computer systems use=
 the typed-in terms to make or collect the payments on the contract.=09Prob=
ably someone keeps a copy of the actual contract somewhere to refer to in c=
ase of disputes or edge cases.

Over millions of contracts, the bank=E2=80=99s humans will=C2=A0type the te=
rms into the computer with a level of accuracy that is probably greater tha=
n 99% but lower than 100%. Which is actually a fair amount=C2=A0of error. S=
ometimes the errors will be extremely prominent=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0there=
=E2=80=99s  that time Citigroup accidentally wired out $900 million to angr=
y hedge funds because the humans pressed the wrong buttons to carry out a l=
oan amendment =E2=80=94=C2=A0but a lot of the time, if a bank and a custome=
r negotiate a fee rate of 0.175% and the bank accidentally types in 0.176%,=
 nobody at the bank or the customer will ever notice. The 0.175% in the neg=
otiated contract is legally binding, but the 0.176% in the computer system =
is practically=C2=A0binding, in the sense that it is what the bank actually=
 collects.
Also if the bank =E2=80=9Caccidentally=E2=80=9D types in the wrong number. =
Wells Fargo & Co.  once got in trouble because some humans in its foreign e=
xchange department would swap digits on its trades:

If the actual correct price to purchase a Euro was 1.0123 dollars, an FX sa=
les specialist would use the big figure trick to switch the price to 1.0213=
 dollars, thus taking more spread (in this example, an additional 89 basis =
points) from the customer.
If the customer actually caught the error, the FX sales specialist would fa=
lsely claim that it was simply a mistake.

But often the customer wouldn=E2=80=99t catch the error, is the point.
You can see why=C2=A0the crypto notion of =E2=80=9Csmart contracts=E2=80=9D=
 is so appealing. Instead of negotiating a contract with humans and then se=
parately typing its terms into a computer program, the humans can just nego=
tiate the computer program directly (or have their computer programs negoti=
ate the program on their behalf) and avoid misunderstandings and ambiguity.=
 Obviously this does not=C2=A0entirely=C2=A0work =E2=80=94=C2=A0you can sti=
ll make a mistake in typing the program; with smart contracts you just make=
 the mistake=C2=A0first=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the idea is attractive.
Anyway here=E2=80=99s another  US Securities and Exchange Commission enforc=
ement action against Wells Fargo about typing contracts into the computers =
wrong:
According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order,=C2=A0certain financial advisers from =
Wells Fargo and its predecessor firms agreed to reduce the firms=E2=80=99 s=
tandard, pre-set advisory fees for certain clients and made handwritten or =
typed changes on the clients=E2=80=99 investment advisory agreements that r=
eflected the reduced fees at the time their accounts were opened. However, =
in certain instances, the account processing employees at Wells Fargo and i=
ts predecessor firms failed to enter the agreed-upon reduced advisory fee r=
ates into the firms=E2=80=99 billing systems when setting up the clients=E2=
=80=99 accounts.
The  SEC=E2=80=99s order goes into more detail, and the more detail include=
s the ominous words =E2=80=9Cby fax=E2=80=9D:

Financial advisors (=E2=80=9CFAs=E2=80=9D) at Wells Fargo predecessor firms=
 AG Edwards and Wachovia used advisory agreements referred to as =E2=80=9Cs=
helf=E2=80=9D agreements to open new advisory client accounts. These =E2=80=
=9Cshelf=E2=80=9D agreements were hard copy versions of their standard advi=
sory agreements. In these =E2=80=9Cshelf=E2=80=9D agreements, the fee sched=
ule section listed the firms=E2=80=99 standard advisory rates. However, FAs=
 at the predecessor firms sometimes negotiated lower advisory rates with cl=
ients and then handwrote or typed the lower negotiated rates on the =E2=80=
=9Cshelf=E2=80=9D agreements. For certain clients, those lower negotiated r=
