10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Hi! Bloomberg is doing a survey of=C2=A0<a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0=
cHM6Ly9ibWVkaWEuaWFkMS5xdWFsdHJpY3MuY29tL2pmZS9mb3JtL1NWXzhCbVBONEFCdVlvYWN=
Ycw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa8047df0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Money Stuff readers</a>; ple=
ase take a few minutes to fill it out. Thanks!</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Sculptor</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Daniel Och founded his hedge fund firm, Och-Zi=
ff Capital Management, in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvU2N1bHB0b3J=
fQ2FwaXRhbF9NYW5hZ2VtZW50/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb9ba028e" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> 1994<=
/a>.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Like most hedge fund firms, Och-Ziff was a limited partnership, m=
eaning among other things that it did not pay corporate income tax: The fir=
m=E2=80=99s income =E2=80=94=C2=A0the fees that it collected from its hedge=
 fund clients, minus its expenses =E2=80=94=C2=A0was taxed as personal inco=
me of Och and his partners.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2007, Och-Ziff did an initial public offeri=
ng, becoming a publicly traded hedge fund management company. This involved=
 becoming a corporation: It is much easier for public shareholders to hold =
shares of a corporation than interests in a partnership, so Och-Ziff went p=
ublic as a corporation, which means paying corporate tax on its income. But=
 it kept the old partnership around: The new corporation became effectively=
 the parent company, controlling the old partnership; public shareholders i=
nvested in the corporation, but Och and his partners kept their shares in t=
he old partnership. Those partnership interests could=C2=A0be converted int=
o corporate shares, and the partners would need to do that conversion if th=
ey wanted to sell their shares on the stock exchange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oversimplifying somewhat, Och and his partners=
 would have to pay tax on those conversions: The fair value of the corporat=
e stock they got on conversion would be taxable income to them. But there w=
ould be an offsetting benefit: Very loosely speaking, Och-Ziff Capital Mana=
gement (the corporation) would get to deduct the fair value of that stock f=
rom its taxable income over the 15 years following conversion.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> As is somewhat typical in IPOs like this, Och-Ziff agreed to give most=
 of that tax benefit to Och and his partners: It entered a =E2=80=9Ctax rec=
eivable agreement=E2=80=9D saying that it would pay the partners 85% of the=
 tax savings that it got from their conversions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the rough economics are that, in going from=
 being partners in a private partnership to shareholders of a public corpor=
ation, Och and his partners would get liquid public shares, but they would =
have to pay a lot of tax. To soften that blow for them, (1) they got to del=
ay that conversion as long as they wanted, and do it in stages, so as not t=
o pay a huge tax bill all at once, and (2) the company promised to pay them=
 most of=C2=A0<em>its=C2=A0</em>tax savings from the conversion, which roug=
hly makes up for the taxes that they have to pay on conversion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another nice sweetener in the IPO is that Och-=
Ziff <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.2614=
26/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE5=
MzEyNTA3MjQ4MjQ1L2Q0MjRiNC5odG0jcm9tNDIxMjlfNjY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB79=
b9f7ca" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> borrowed $750 million</a> and paid most of it out to Och a=
nd his partners. My understanding is that they did not have to pay tax on t=
his money: As partners of a partnership, they owed tax on the partnership=
=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>income</em>, but not on money it=C2=A0<em>borrowed</em>=
; the borrowing was basically a way for them to cash out some future income=
 at the time of the IPO and only pay taxes later when the income was actual=
ly earned.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway then time passed, Och-Ziff had some tro=
ubles, it paid a big bribery settlement, Och stepped down as chief executiv=
e officer because of=C2=A0the bribery scandal, the firm was renamed Sculpto=
r Capital Management Inc., Och=E2=80=99s estranged former prot=C3=A9g=C3=A9=
 Jimmy Levin took over as CEO, Levin got paid a lot of money even as perfor=
mance wasn=E2=80=99t great, Och started agitating for changes, and Sculptor=
=E2=80=99s board decided to sell the company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMjEvZXZlcnlvbmUtd2FudHMtYS1waWVjZS1vZi1zY3VscHR=
vcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODMwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2=
U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA4MzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB26d6462d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked about</a> the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMjMvY291bGQtc2N1bHB0b3I=
tYmUtYmV0dGVyLW9yLWNoZWFwZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgzMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZG=
l1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwODMwJnV0bV9jYW1wY=
Wlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB58b02df9" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  sale proce=
ss</a> a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.=
261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgt=
MjkvZ3JheXNjYWxlLWNhbi1iZS1hLWJpdGNvaW4tZXRmP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MzAyM19NT05FWVN=
UVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMD=
gzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5b9a7685" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">  few times</a> over the last two weeks; the current status is that Sc=
ulptor has=C2=A0agreed to sell itself to a firm called Rithm Capital Corp. =
for $11.15 per share, a group of hedge fund managers led by Boaz Weinstein =
has jumped in with a topping bid of $12.25 per share, Sculptor=E2=80=99s bo=
ard argues that this bid is not particularly real (not fully financed and k=
ind of vague) and it has refused to engage with the Weinstein bidders.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Och has been publicly pushing Sculptor to enga=
ge with Weinstein. He has argued that=C2=A0Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has bru=
shed off Weinstein because it is protecting Jimmy Levin: He is the CEO, the=
y are tight with him and they want him to keep his well-paid job; Rithm wou=
ld retain Levin to run Sculptor=E2=80=99s funds (though at a lower salary, =
capped at $30 million a year versus the $146 million he got in 2021), while=
 Weinstein probably would not. Och argues that public shareholders would be=
 better off getting $12.25 than $11.15, and that Sculptor=E2=80=99s board i=
s depriving them of the extra $1.10 to protect their buddy Levin.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sculptor says that this is nonsense, that the =
sale process was designed to maximize shareholder value, that the board is =
independent of Levin and didn=E2=80=99t care at all about whether potential=
 buyers would retain him, and that its skepticism about Weinstein comes pur=
ely from the fact that, in months of discussions, Weinstein has never put i=
n a fully financed bid.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it also has more specific arguments about =
Och=E2=80=99s own position. Yesterday Sculptor=E2=80=99s lawyers sent <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIzMj=
I0MjcwL2Q0OTQ0NTZkZXg5OTEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc98a92cd" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 two</a> very punchy <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0=
MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIzMjI0MjcwL2Q0OTQ0NTZkZXg5OTIuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB32c1ad0f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> letters</a> to Och and his lawyers, saying that h=
is efforts to sink the Rithm deal and bring in Weinstein are driven by =E2=
=80=9Ceconomic self-interest and personal vendettas.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Start with the personal vendettas. Sculptor <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTI=
zMjI0MjcwL2Q0OTQ0NTZkZXg5OTIuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC32c1ad0f" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> traces</a> these back to the bribery scandal:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Faced with massive capital withdrawals in the =
wake of the scandal and restrictive regulatory penalties that barred the Co=
mpany from key investor channels, the Company had no choice but to attempt =
to distance itself from Mr. Och, including by ultimately rebranding as Scul=
ptor.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In December 2017, the independent directors of=
 the Board unanimously voted to recommend that Mr. Och be removed as CEO. M=
r. Och refused to recognize the idea that his continued presence at the Com=
pany was detrimental to its future success. Instead, he became enraged by t=
he perceived disloyalty of Company executives and Board members who made th=
is decision. Chief among those whom Mr. Och blamed for his exit from the Co=
mpany is Mr. Levin, its current chief executive and chief investment office=
r, whom Mr. Och had previously anointed as his heir-apparent. Mr. Och conte=
mporaneously instructed a group of his allies, including certain members of=
 the Och Group and Mr. Rutman: =E2=80=9CWe have to make clear that I/we wil=
l be the winning team=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9CJimmy [Levin] cannot be th=
e winning team.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so, Sculptor argues, Och has had it out fo=
r Levin ever since. He has complained, for instance, that the pay deal Levi=
n has negotiated with Rithm is too high, but Sculptor points out that =E2=
=80=9Cwhen Mr. Och was CEO, he regularly approved compensation for Mr. Levi=
n in excess of the cap=E2=80=9D on his pay in the Rithm deal. Also Sculptor=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE5MzEy=
NTIzMjI0MjcwL2Q0OTQ0NTZkZXg5OTEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCc98a92cd" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> says=C2=A0that</a> =E2=80=9CMr. Och=E2=80=99s purported concern for p=
ublic stockholders is in stark contrast to his record when running the Comp=
any. Mr. Och took home $3.3 billion since 2007 while the Company=E2=80=99s =
stock price dropped by 96%.=E2=80=9D That comes with a little graph showing=
 how much money Och got over time (a green line going up) versus the Sculpt=
or stock price (a red line mostly going down).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then there are the economic interests. <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIz=
MjI0MjcwL2Q0OTQ0NTZkZXg5OTIuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cD32c1ad0f" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> Sculptor says</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On July 6, 2023, the Och Group entered into a =
confidentiality agreement with Rithm so they could discuss a potential tran=
saction. Over the next two weeks, Rithm responded to extensive requests for=
 information from the Och Group and engaged with them on a number of issues=
 they raised as conditions for supporting any transaction. The issues that =
Mr. Och raised in those discussions made clear to the Company that Mr. Och=
=E2=80=99s focus was on continuing to inflict additional pay cuts on Mr. Le=
vin and on maximizing his own economic interests not shared with public sto=
ckholders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example, the Och Group focused heavily on =
the TRA asset that Mr. Och had bestowed on himself and the other Och Group =
members at the time of the Company=E2=80=99s IPO in 2007. The TRA assets ha=
ve allowed the Och Group to reap over $150 million in payments from the Com=
pany in connection with the use of certain tax assets that had been created=
 at the time of the IPO. The TRA by its terms expressly contemplated change=
-of-control transactions such as the merger by providing for assumptions fa=
vorable to the Och Group in calculating TRA payments but did not provide fo=
r any required acceleration of those TRA payments, which instead would cont=
inue to be paid over a several years. Nevertheless, in his discussions with=
 Rithm, Mr. Och requested that, as part of closing any transaction, Rithm a=
gree to prepay a significant portion of the more than $170 million in estim=
ated remaining TRA payments, a substantial portion of which would be paid t=
o the Och Group. Moreover, the Och Group demanded a highly favorable discou=
nt rate on the prepayment. Similarly, the Och Group insisted as a condition=
 of supporting any transaction that Rithm agree to pay them an additional $=
5.5 million in cash for legal expenses incurred in connection with the Comp=
any=E2=80=99s sales process, including counsel costs related to negotiating=
 for their own economic benefits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The transaction under discussion between the O=
ch Group and Rithm would have included the option for a rollover of the Cla=
ss A Unit interests that they hold, in a fully tax-deferred transaction, wh=
ich would allow them to avoid recognizing significant taxable gain in exces=
s of proceeds to be received in the transaction (as a result of taxable gai=
n attributable in large part to tax-deferred distributions previously recei=
ved by the Och Group).</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is: Any potential buyer of Sculptor (Rith=
m, Weinstein, the anonymous =E2=80=9CBidder D=E2=80=9D who walked away from=
 Sculptor earlier in its sale process) will prefer to have Och=E2=80=99s su=
pport, or at least grudging acquiescence, partly because he is a Sculptor s=
hareholder and can vote against the deal but mostly because if he doesn=E2=
=80=99t like the deal he can create bad publicity and perhaps drive away cl=
ients. And so Rithm talked to Och to seek his support, and (according to Sc=
ulptor) what they talked about was mostly (1) revenge on Jimmy Levin and (2=
) Och=E2=80=99s own tax interests.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The tax receivable agreement, or TRA: =
Some companies have TRAs that accelerate on a change of control, so that, i=
nstead of paying out the tax benefits over years as the company realizes ta=
xable income, they just pay a big lump sum when the merger happens. Sculpto=
r=E2=80=99s TRA doesn=E2=80=99t do that: The buyer has to assume the TRA an=
d keep making payments,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> but it doesn=E2=80=99t have to pay the benefits all at once. Och, acco=
rding to Sculptor, wanted the buyer to make the payments all at once=C2=A0a=
s a condition of his support.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The =
rollover: Och=C2=A0still has lots of partnership units that he hasn=E2=80=
=99t yet converted into stock. One normal way to do a cash merger of Sculpt=
or would be to convert all of Och=E2=80=99s partnership units into Sculptor=
 shares and then cash them out at $11.15, the same price as the public shar=
eholders. But this would require him to immediately pay taxes on the $11.15=
 of proceeds. Which doesn=E2=80=99t sound that bad: If you get $11.15 and p=
ay taxes on it, you still have, you know, $9. Except remember that $750 mil=
lion loan that Och-Ziff took out at the IPO? Och-Ziff/Sculptor has paid =E2=
=80=9Ctax-deferred distributions=E2=80=9D to its partners: Effectively Scul=
ptor/Och-Ziff=E2=80=99s partners were able to take out cash in excess of th=
e company=E2=80=99s income without paying taxes on it, deferring the taxes.=
 At this point, if they sold for $11.15 per share, they would have =E2=80=
=9Csignificant taxable gain in excess of proceeds to be received in the tra=
nsaction,=E2=80=9D meaning that much of the $11.15 would go to taxes. To av=
oid that, Och wants a buyer to keep the partnership around and let him keep=
 his partnership units until he decides to convert them. This is potentiall=
y a pain for the buyer, who might not=C2=A0<em>want</em> Och around as a pa=
rtner, but it is, says Sculptor, the price of his support.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are basically three sets of interests he=
re:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders want =
the deal that gives them the highest price per share.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">Jimmy Levin wants the deal that lets him keep his job a=
t the highest pay rate.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Dan Och wa=
nts the deal that gives him the highest tax benefits.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The only =E2=80=9Clegitimate=E2=80=9D interest=
, the one that Sculptor=E2=80=99s board is supposed to care about, is that =
of the shareholders. Och says that the board really cares about Levin=E2=80=
=99s interests and has refused to take higher bids in order to preserve Lev=
in=E2=80=99s job, and that he is fighting for shareholder interests. The bo=
ard says that that=E2=80=99s wrong, that <em>it</em> is fighting for shareh=
older interests, and that Och is out there trying to blow up a good deal fo=
r shareholders=C2=A0to maximize his own tax benefits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally, a continuing oddity of this deal=
 is that Weinstein and friends aren=E2=80=99t allowed to talk publicly abou=
t it: As we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/325592=
82.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtM=
DgtMjkvZ3JheXNjYWxlLWNhbi1iZS1hLWJpdGNvaW4tZXRmP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MzAyM19NT05F=
WVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI=
