" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">  discussed</a>, Weinstein signed a nondisclosure agree=
ment with Sculptor that prohibits him from making public bids or otherwise =
talking about the deal process. The Weinstein group has privately offered $=
12.25 per share, and the board has publicized that offer and said that it=
=E2=80=99s too uncertain, but Weinstein isn=E2=80=99t allowed to make his c=
ase publicly.=C2=A0It would be interesting to see Weinstein make the case t=
hat, you know, =E2=80=9C$12.25 per share is more than $11.15 and I really c=
an close the deal, so my offer is better for shareholders.=E2=80=9D But he =
can=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s part of why Och has been so pub=
lic about criticizing the board and the sale process: He is allowed to, whi=
le the actual competing bidder is not. But, as the board says, his own inte=
rests are not quite the same as those of the shareholders.</p>
