<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At a big bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0or other big fina=
ncial firm, or other big company generally =E2=80=94=C2=A0most contracts ar=
e fulfilled by computer. Often the contracts are also <em>negotiated</em> b=
y computer =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you open a credit card on a company=E2=80=99s =
website, probably no human negotiated its terms with you =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=
 often they aren=E2=80=99t. Often the process is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A human at the bank negotiates a cont=
ract (a mortgage, an exotic derivative, a corporate loan restructuring, wha=
tever) with a human counterparty.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
The human at the bank types the terms of the contract into the bank=E2=80=
=99s computer systems, or hands the contract to some other, lower-paid huma=
n at the bank to type them in.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The=
 bank=E2=80=99s computer systems use the typed-in terms to make or collect =
the payments on the contract.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Prob=
ably someone keeps a copy of the actual contract somewhere to refer to in c=
ase of disputes or edge cases.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over millions of contracts, the bank=E2=80=99s=
 humans will=C2=A0type the terms into the computer with a level of accuracy=
 that is probably greater than 99% but lower than 100%. Which is actually a=
 fair amount=C2=A0of error. Sometimes the errors will be extremely prominen=
t=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0there=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMTcvY2l0aS1jYW4tdC1oYXZlLWl0cy05MDAtbWlsbGlvbi=
1iYWNrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MzAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nvd=
XJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDgzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB766f3773" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> that time</a> Citigroup accident=
ally wired out $900 million to angry hedge funds because the humans pressed=
 the wrong buttons to carry out a loan amendment =E2=80=94=C2=A0but a lot o=
f the time, if a bank and a customer negotiate a fee rate of 0.175% and the=
 bank accidentally types in 0.176%, nobody at the bank or the customer will=
 ever notice. The 0.175% in the negotiated contract is legally binding, but=
 the 0.176% in the computer system is <em>practically=C2=A0</em>binding, in=
 the sense that it is what the bank actually collects.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also if the bank =E2=80=9Caccidentally=E2=80=
=9D types in the wrong number. Wells Fargo &amp; Co. <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMjgvd2VsbHMtZmFyZ28tc3dhcHBlZC1=
zb21lLWRpZ2l0cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODMwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJn=
V0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA4MzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c=
3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdf528ae6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> once got in trouble</a>=
 because some humans in its foreign exchange department would swap digits o=
n its trades:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the actual correct price to purchase a Euro=
 was 1.0123 dollars, an FX sales specialist would use the big figure trick =
to switch the price to 1.0213 dollars, thus taking more spread (in this exa=
mple, an additional 89 basis points) from the customer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the customer actually caught the error, the=
 FX sales specialist would falsely claim that it was simply a mistake.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But often the customer <em>wouldn=E2=80=99t</e=
m> catch the error, is the point.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can see why=C2=A0the crypto notion of =E2=
=80=9Csmart contracts=E2=80=9D is so appealing. Instead of negotiating a co=
ntract with humans and then separately typing its terms into a computer pro=
gram, the humans can just negotiate the computer program directly (or have =
their computer programs negotiate the program on their behalf) and avoid mi=
sunderstandings and ambiguity. Obviously this does not=C2=A0<em>entirely=C2=
=A0</em>work =E2=80=94=C2=A0you can still make a mistake in typing the prog=
ram; with smart contracts you just make the mistake=C2=A0<em>first=C2=A0</e=
m>=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the idea is attractive.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here=E2=80=99s another <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2=
VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy0xNTk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB843e=
153d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> US Securities and Exchange Commission enforcement action</a>=
 against Wells Fargo about typing contracts into the computers wrong:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC=E2=80=99s ord=
er,=C2=A0certain financial advisers from Wells Fargo and its predecessor fi=
rms agreed to reduce the firms=E2=80=99 standard, pre-set advisory fees for=
 certain clients and made handwritten or typed changes on the clients=E2=80=
=99 investment advisory agreements that reflected the reduced fees at the t=
ime their accounts were opened. However, in certain instances, the account =
processing employees at Wells Fargo and its predecessor firms failed to ent=
er the agreed-upon reduced advisory fee rates into the firms=E2=80=99 billi=
ng systems when setting up the clients=E2=80=99 accounts.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0=
aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjMvMzQtOTgyMjEucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc1baf5c4" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> SEC=E2=80=99s order</a> goes into more detail, and the more detail in=
cludes the ominous words =E2=80=9Cby fax=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Financial advisors (=E2=80=9CFAs=E2=80=9D) at =
Wells Fargo predecessor firms AG Edwards and Wachovia used advisory agreeme=
nts referred to as =E2=80=9Cshelf=E2=80=9D agreements to open new advisory =
client accounts. These =E2=80=9Cshelf=E2=80=9D agreements were hard copy ve=
rsions of their standard advisory agreements. In these =E2=80=9Cshelf=E2=80=
=9D agreements, the fee schedule section listed the firms=E2=80=99 standard=
 advisory rates. However, FAs at the predecessor firms sometimes negotiated=
 lower advisory rates with clients and then handwrote or typed the lower ne=
gotiated rates on the =E2=80=9Cshelf=E2=80=9D agreements. For certain clien=
ts, those lower negotiated rates were not entered into the predecessor firm=
s=E2=80=99 billing systems. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Beginning in at least 2009, Wells Fargo=E2=80=
=99s FAs were responsible for completing investment advisory account docume=
ntation for new Wells Fargo advisory client accounts. The Wells Fargo FAs w=
ere likewise permitted to negotiate lower rates with the clients and to han=
dwrite or type those lower rates on the =E2=80=9Cshelf=E2=80=9D agreements.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Wells Fargo FAs then submitted the complet=
ed account setup documents, including the =E2=80=9Cshelf=E2=80=9D agreement=
s, to a team of Wells Fargo Account Setup Processors (=E2=80=9CASPs=E2=80=
=9D) by fax. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the end of the account setup process, after=
 the ASPs transferred the client information from the client account setup =
documents, an automated notification was generated by the account setup too=
l and sent to the FAs responsible for the clients=E2=80=99 accounts. The no=
tification included the client=E2=80=99s new account information, including=
 advisory fee rates. The FAs could then review this account information and=
 report any issues or discrepancies. However, Wells Fargo did not have poli=
cies and procedures requiring the FAs to acknowledge receipt of or to revie=
w these notifications or confirm the accuracy of the new account informatio=
n.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I assume that there were some (many?) examples=
 of Wells Fargo financial advisers who made it a priority, upon getting bac=
k new-account-setup notifications for their new clients, to check the fee r=
ates against their handwritten markups of the shelf agreement to make sure =
that they weren=E2=80=99t making too much money from those clients. But, un=
surprisingly, there were some who didn=E2=80=99t.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Free riding</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Roughly speaking, the way it works is that if =
you open a brokerage account online and say =E2=80=9Chi I have sent you a $=
1 million check to buy so many stocks,=E2=80=9D the broker will let you buy=
 $200,000 worth of stocks right now, even before the check arrives. When I =
say it like that it doesn=E2=80=99t sound very smart. To be fair:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">$200,000 is a lot less than $1 million=
, so if you did send the check it=E2=80=99s fine.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">If you didn=E2=80=99t send the check, your stocks stay in t=
he brokerage account, so the broker can just sell them and get most or all =
of its money back. You can=E2=80=99t sell the stocks and=C2=A0<em>withdraw=
=C2=A0</em>the money until your check clears.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">If you didn=E2=80=99t send the check, you will probably get in =
trouble.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The sophisticated illegal way to take advantag=
e of this is called =E2=80=9Cfree riding=E2=80=9D: You buy $200,000 worth o=
f stocks, you wait a bit, you see if they go up; if they go up, you send in=
 the promised check, sell the stocks and collect your winnings. If they go =
down, you never send the check and leave the broker with the losses. This i=
s not a great idea =E2=80=94=C2=A0you will get in trouble =E2=80=94=C2=A0bu=
t it happens.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The unsophisticated illegal way to take =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0advantage? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0of this is just, you have $0.09 in your =
bank account, you call the broker and say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m sending a ch=
eck for $1 million ha ha ha,=E2=80=9D the broker lets you buy $200,000 of s=
tocks, you buy them, they go up, and you never send in the check because wh=
ere are you going to get $1 million. The downsides of this trade are (1) yo=
u will get in trouble and (2) you don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0make any money even if=
 the stocks do go up. The upside is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I guess it is funny? A l=
ittle? At least it is something to pass the time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2xpdHJl=
bGVhc2VzL2xyLTI1ODE2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBafd87415" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Anyway</a>:=
</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission on Augu=
st 25, 2023, charged 23-year-old Deyonte Jahtori Anthony ("Anthony"), of Co=
ncord, North Carolina, with conducting a fraudulent "free-riding" scheme in=
 which he bought nearly $200,000 in securities without paying for them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC's complaint alleges that, between July=
 1 and 6, 2022, Anthony opened a new brokerage account using a fraudulent a=
pplication on which he overstated his personal income and then made $1 mill=
ion in bogus deposits from his bank account, which held only nine cents at =
the time. The complaint also states that, before Anthony's deposits reverse=
d for insufficient funds in his bank account, he used "immediate access" cr=
edit extended to him by his broker-dealer to purchase $199,956.65 in securi=
ties. According to the complaint, Anthony's broker-dealer discovered the sc=
heme before Anthony could make any profits, froze his account, and liquidat=
ed his holdings.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0=
aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMy9jb21wMjU4MTYucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc905a=
917" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> SEC complaint</a> is a wild ride. You get some GameStop:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After making $1 million in unfunde=
d deposits from his bank account, Anthony then made a series of exchange-tr=
aded fund (=E2=80=9CETF=E2=80=9D) and equity purchases =E2=80=94=C2=A0inclu=
ding Apple, Inc. (=E2=80=9CApple=E2=80=9D), AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc=
. (=E2=80=9CAMC=E2=80=9D), GameStop Corporation (=E2=80=9CGameStop=E2=80=9D=
) and Tesla, Inc. (=E2=80=9CTesla=E2=80=9D) =E2=80=94=C2=A0totaling $199,95=
6.65 using the =E2=80=9Cimmediate access=E2=80=9D credit extended to him by=
 Broker A.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You get Anthony=E2=80=99s finances:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Around the time of Anthony=E2=80=99s free-ridi=
ng, employment records show that Anthony was hired on June 23, 2022, as a f=
ast-food restaurant worker at an Auntie Anne=E2=80=99s pretzel franchise in=
 Concord, North Carolina, where he worked four shifts totaling 21 hours bet=
ween June 25, 2022 and July 2, 2022.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For his work, Anthony earned a total of $333.0=
9, and was then terminated from his job on July 9, 2022, after failing to s=
how up to work. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Once his Broker A brokerage account was open, =
Anthony linked it to a bank account in his name at Bank A, which had a bala=
nce of $0.09 at the time of his brokerage account application.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There was no way for him to win:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anthony opened a Broker A =E2=80=
=9CSelf Invest=E2=80=9D account, a type of account for which Broker A exten=
ds up to $200,000 in =E2=80=9Cimmediate access=E2=80=9D credit for pending =
deposits. Such accounts also are limited to $500,000 in automated clearingh=
ouse (=E2=80=9CACH=E2=80=9D) deposits per day, and deposits are subject to =
a seven-day hold before withdrawals are allowed.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So even if his stocks went up, he couldn=E2=80=
=99t withdraw money until his original deposit actually cleared. Which it w=
ouldn=E2=80=99t, because his original deposits were =E2=80=9Cfive ACH depos=
its online totaling $1 million from his Bank A account=E2=80=9D and he had =
9 cents in that account. But his stocks=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>go up:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All five of Anthony=E2=80=99s depo=
sits ultimately reversed for lack of funds in his associated Bank A account=
. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Therafter, Broker A liquidated his holdings for a net prof=
it of $7,127.25.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Good for him. He settled the case for a promis=
e not to do it again and a fine to be determined later. Someone should hire=
 him as a trader. He has all the important skills: creativity, ethical flex=
ibility, the ability to pick stocks that go up. Also a sense of humor:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When asked why he made the $1 mill=
ion in unfunded deposits without having funds to cover the transactions, An=
thony excused his conduct as =E2=80=9Ca joke=E2=80=9D and said that he =E2=
=80=9Cnever really thought of it as fraud.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
