<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Short swing</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One of the less important US insider trading r=
ules is the =E2=80=9Cshort swing profits=E2=80=9D rule, Section 16(b) of th=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9kaXZpc2lvbnMvY29ycGZpbi9ndWlkYW5jZS9zZWMxNmludGV=
ycA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeb1d56b6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Exchange Act</a>,=C2=A0which=
 says that insiders of public companies aren=E2=80=99t supposed to make pro=
fits by rapidly trading in and out of their stock. Intuitively, if you=E2=
=80=99re the chief executive officer of a company and you know that earning=
s are going to be disappointing, you can=E2=80=99t sell all your stock the =
day before earnings and buy it back a week later; if you know that earnings=
 are going to be good, you can=E2=80=99t buy more stock before earnings and=
 sell it a week later. More specifically, the rule says that if you do a pu=
rchase and a sale of your company=E2=80=99s stock within six months of each=
 other (in either order), and the purchase price is less than the sale pric=
e, you have to give up the profits to the company. There are various <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9kaXZpc2lvbnMvY29ycGZpbi9ndWlkYW5jZS9zZWMxNmludGVycA/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cCeb1d56b6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">technicalities</a>=C2=A0about what c=
ounts as a purchase or a sale or ownership =E2=80=94=C2=A0there is a whole =
industry of Section 16 lawyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0and this rule is one reason t=
hat activist investors tend to stay below 10% of their target companies: If=
 they go over 10%, they become Section 16 insiders, and their trading is re=
stricted.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, with actual CEOs it just doesn=E2=
=80=99t come up=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>much, because most CEOs are at leas=
t vaguely aware of the rule and anyway are not actively trading their stock=
 all that frequently.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">CEOs=E2=80=99=C2=A0children, though, who knows=
. Here is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/325592=
82.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NjY1ODEvM=
DAwMTIwOTE5MTIzMDQ3NjE1L3hzbEYzNDVYMDUvZG9jNC54bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Ba90d3bde" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">securities filing</a> from Travis Boersma, the chairman =
and co-founder of Dutch Bros Inc., a publicly traded drive-through coffee c=
hain. Apparently his adult son was actively trading Dutch Bros stock withou=
t telling him, doing stuff like buying 19.36 shares for $62.01 each ($1,200=
.53 total) and selling them later that same day for $62.24 (a $4.45 profit)=
. Selling 25.45=C2=A0shares at $29.44 one day and buying back 25.43=C2=A0sh=
ares that same day at $29.45 (a 24-cent profit). Buying 130.38 shares for $=
29.80 in May and selling 136.19 shares at $29.36 in August (a $113.27 profi=
t). Stuff like that.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also=C2=A0options though.=C2=A0On Tuesday, Aug=
. 8, the son bought three $26 strike call options expiring that Friday, pay=
ing $230 for each of them; he sold one that day for $239.98 (a $9.98 profit=
) and two more that Wednesday =E2=80=94=C2=A0after the company <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32559282.261426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NjY1ODEvMDAwMTg2NjU4MTIzMDAwMTA4L=
2EyMDIzLXEyX2V4OTkxLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe886f9cd" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">announ=
ced</a> good earnings and a new CEO and the stock rallied =E2=80=94 for $54=
9.99 each, a profit of almost $640.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose after almost doubling his three-digi=
t investment=C2=A0on well-timed options trades ahead of=C2=A0corporate news=
, he =E2=80=A6=C2=A0confessed? bragged? something =E2=80=A6=C2=A0to his dad=
, because yesterday Boersma disclosed his son=E2=80=99s trades going back t=
o 2021 with this awkward footnote:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pursuant to Section 16 reporting r=
equirements, the Form 4 reflects purchases and sales of the Issuer's Class =
A common stock and derivative securities that were made by the Reporting Pe=
rson's adult son. The amount of profit realized by the applicable short-swi=
ng transactions is approximately $8,500 and has been paid to the Issuer, as=
 required. The Reporting Person was recently notified of the transactions b=
y his son, resulting in today's filing.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arguably the core purpose of Section 16 really=
 is to prevent corporate executives=E2=80=99 adult children from day-tradin=
g options on their parents=E2=80=99 companies going into earnings so, you k=
now, great.</p>
